igidity of the greater part of the country. The phenomenon of global warming, if it occurs, will lessen this coldness, but its impact on temperature extremes, sea ice regimes, vegetation, snow distribution, permafrost, glaciers, lakes, rivers, and mountain hazards are all the subject of intensive research -- the highlights of which are reviewed in Canada's Cold Environments. Eleven of Canada's leading geographers, geologists, and ecologists provide an authoritative yet readable scientific statement about the physical nature of Canada's coldness. They focus on the distinctive attributes of Canada's cold environments, their temporal and spatial variability, and the constraints that coldness places on human activity. The book is aimed at environmental scientists at all levels who need informed overviews of the substantive findings on a range of cold-related topics.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aSCIENCE / Earth Sciences / Geography.2bisacsh1 aBarry, Roger G., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aClague, John J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFord, Derek C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFrench, Hugh M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGardner, James S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLedrew, Ellsworth F., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRitchie, James C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRouse, Wayne R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSlaymaker, Olav, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aSlaymaker, Olav, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSmith, Michael W., econtributor.4ctb4h